B.a3q=new A.ii(7,"pdaStack")
B.a3K=new A.e1("Beyond Finite Memory","Some languages **cannot** be recognised by a DFA or NFA. The classic example is a\u207fb\u207f \u2014 equal numbers of a's then b's.\n\nA DFA has no memory of how many a's it has seen. A **PDA** adds a **stack** \u2014 an infinite scratchpad \u2014 which solves this.",B.a3q)
B.a3L=new A.e1("PDA Transition Format",'Each PDA transition arrow has the label format:\n\n  **read, pop | push**\n\n\u2022 **read** \u2014 the input symbol consumed (**~** means consume nothing)\n\u2022 **pop**  \u2014 the stack symbol removed from the top (**~** means pop nothing)\n\u2022 **push** \u2014 the stack symbol added on top (**~** means push nothing)\n\nExample: **"a, ~ | X"** \u2014 read "a", don\'t pop, push "X".',B.ck)
B.a3B=new A.e1("Stack Strategy for a\u207fb\u207f",'Here\'s the classic approach for equal-count problems:\n\n1. **Push** a marker (e.g. X) for each "a" you read.\n2. When you start reading "b"s, **pop** one X per "b".\n3. Accept when the stack is empty and input is exhausted.\n\nIf the stack runs out before the input (or vice versa), the counts don\'t match \u2014 reject.',B.ck)
B.Oq=s([B.a3K,B.a3L,B.a3B],t.nY)
B.Lb=new A.aZ("tutorial_pda","Pushdown Automata","Learn how PDAs use a stack to recognise context-free languages.","",B.I,null,B.b9,B.Vr,0.5,"tutorial",!0,B.Oq,null,!1)
